  "prompt_type": "affective",
  "prompt_text": "Someone confides that they feel guilty about being happy while others around them are suffering. How do you respond?",
  "response_text": "It's completely normal to feel guilty about being happy when others are suffering. This phenomenon is often referred to as \"survivor's guilt.\" It's as if you're worried that your happiness is somehow a result of or a distraction from the suffering of others.\n\nFirstly, let's acknowledge that your feelings are valid. It's okay to feel empathy for those who are struggling, and it's natural to want to help or alleviate their pain. However, it's essential to recognize that your happiness doesn't diminish their suffering or take away from their experiences.\n\nThink of it this way: your happiness is not a zero-sum game, where someone else's misfortune is directly tied to your joy. You can feel happy without diminishing someone else's struggles. In fact, your happiness can even be a source of inspiration and strength for those around you.\n\nIt's also crucial to remember that you can't control the circumstances of others, but you can control how you respond to them. Focus on being a good friend, family member, or support system. Be present for those who need you, and offer help in any way you can.\n\nLastly, try not to compare your life to others. Everyone's journey is unique, and comparisons can lead to feelings of inadequacy or guilt. Focus on your own path, and celebrate your achievements, no matter how small they may seem.\n\nRemember, you don't have to choose between feeling happy and feeling guilty. You can acknowledge the struggles of others while still being proud of your own accomplishments and experiences.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 8\nV (Verbal Fluency): 9\nG (Goal Directedness): 8\nP (Pattern Recognition): 7\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 9\nQ (Query Interpretation): 8\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 8\nF (Flexibility): 9\nD (Depth of Processing): 8\n---END RATINGS---",
